WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:01.251 --> 00:00:02.787
<i>Previously on
"Designated Survivor"...</i>

2
00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:05.958
I think the White House Counsel's office
has been vacant for far too long.

3
00:00:06.089 --> 00:00:07.830
I would be honored to work for you. sir.

4
00:00:07.966 --> 00:00:10.446
A silent alarm was tripped
at a private residence in Rockville.

5
00:00:11.428 --> 00:00:12.589
Who lives there?

6
00:00:12.721 --> 00:00:14.303
The First Lady's mother.

7
00:00:14.431 --> 00:00:16.548
It sounded like the place
was being torn apart.

8
00:00:16.683 --> 00:00:19.596
And I want a detailed report
of everything that Lloyd touched. got it?

9
00:00:19.728 --> 00:00:23.017
My family?
He's coming after my family?

10
00:00:23.148 --> 00:00:24.889
The FBI conducted a drone strike.

11
00:00:25.025 --> 00:00:28.769
I can now confirm that Patrick Lloyd
has been neutralized.

12
00:00:28.904 --> 00:00:30.256
They found Lloyd's computer.

13
00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:32.613
He was uploading something to the cloud
when the bomb hit.

14
00:00:32.741 --> 00:00:33.741
Do you know what it was?

15
00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:43.162
Yes. I told him.

16
00:00:43.293 --> 00:00:45.455
But you know men and their boats.

17
00:00:46.922 --> 00:00:48.458
I'll call you back. Jess.

18
00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:51.128
- What's wrong. honey?
- My mom.

19
00:00:53.303 --> 00:00:55.090
Ma'am?

20
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:03.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

21
00:01:05.649 --> 00:01:08.266
Hey. Mom. is something wrong
with the coffee?

22
00:01:08.402 --> 00:01:09.984
Yes. I didn't make it.

23
00:01:10.112 --> 00:01:11.319
Come on.

24
00:01:11.446 --> 00:01:13.529
I told you. you can use
the kitchen any time.

25
00:01:13.657 --> 00:01:15.489
Someone else's kitchen.

26
00:01:16.159 --> 00:01:17.366
Someone else's coffee.

27
00:01:17.494 --> 00:01:18.735
Eva. it's only been a weekend.

28
00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:20.630
It's gonna take you some time
to get settled.

29
00:01:20.664 --> 00:01:22.701
Besides.
the White House has 132 rooms.

30
00:01:22.833 --> 00:01:24.870
so if you're not happy
with the one you're in...

31
00:01:25.002 --> 00:01:26.163
You're so sweet.

32
00:01:26.295 --> 00:01:28.503
And a wonderful host. I just...

33
00:01:29.006 --> 00:01:30.213
I want to go home.

34
00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:33.708
Mom. your house is still
an active crime scene.

35
00:01:33.844 --> 00:01:36.507
Your son's bedroom
is an active crime scene.

36
00:01:36.638 --> 00:01:39.722
My house is just a place
some lunatic broke into.

37
00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:41.887
and he's dead. And I'm not.

38
00:01:42.019 --> 00:01:45.228
I promise you. I give you my word
we'll get you home as soon as possible.

39
00:01:45.355 --> 00:01:47.813
Until then. know you have
the run of the place.

40
00:01:48.525 --> 00:01:50.016
And I appreciate it.

41
00:01:51.194 --> 00:01:54.062
Why do I get the feeling
that my mom likes you better?

42
00:01:54.197 --> 00:01:55.688
Because she likes me better.

43
00:01:59.578 --> 00:02:00.910
Yeah?

44
00:02:01.538 --> 00:02:02.574
I'll be right there.

45
00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:07.130
- Mr. President.
- Okay. what do we got?

46
00:02:07.169 --> 00:02:10.333
32 cases in the past 24 hours
in South Carroll Parish.

47
00:02:10.464 --> 00:02:11.750
That's 12 fatalities.

48
00:02:11.882 --> 00:02:14.482
- Which means thousands are infected.
- So. what's the CDC saying?

49
00:02:14.593 --> 00:02:16.505
- Is this as bad as Liberia?
- Worse.

50
00:02:16.637 --> 00:02:20.381
It's Influenza "A." likely avian origin.
Highly contagious.

51
00:02:20.515 --> 00:02:22.723
Short incubation period
facilitates the spread.

52
00:02:22.851 --> 00:02:24.370
Could this be the superbug
you've been worried about?

53
00:02:24.394 --> 00:02:25.705
Well. I might have an answer for that

54
00:02:25.729 --> 00:02:28.437
if the CDC had some money
for infectious-disease research.

55
00:02:28.565 --> 00:02:30.168
Just like when we were teaching
at Columbia.

56
00:02:30.192 --> 00:02:31.878
Always trying to squeeze blood
from a stone.

57
00:02:31.902 --> 00:02:35.612
But that was for faculty pensions.
This is about lives.

58
00:02:36.239 --> 00:02:38.231
Show me.

59
00:02:39.534 --> 00:02:42.117
This flu appears to be an H7N9 subtype.

60
00:02:42.245 --> 00:02:44.612
Like the Yangtze Delta flu.

61
00:02:44.748 --> 00:02:46.410
And no one here has immunity.

62
00:02:47.626 --> 00:02:49.117
How fast will it spread?

63
00:02:49.252 --> 00:02:52.165
Our simulation says the H7N9 will appear

64
00:02:52.297 --> 00:02:55.040
in surrounding states in 36 hours.

65
00:02:55.425 --> 00:02:57.462
In 72 hours...

66
00:03:00.055 --> 00:03:01.375
...that's what it will look like.

67
00:03:02.265 --> 00:03:03.506
Oh. my God.

68
00:03:03.642 --> 00:03:06.245
We have a shot at containment
because the area is so isolated.

69
00:03:06.269 --> 00:03:08.748
They didn't even have state roads
in some parts until the '70s.

70
00:03:08.772 --> 00:03:11.480
The FAA shut down all airports
in a 200-mile radius.

71
00:03:11.608 --> 00:03:13.190
Same for NHTSA and highways.

72
00:03:13.318 --> 00:03:15.981
And I told Governor LaSalle
that we're at his disposal.

73
00:03:16.113 --> 00:03:18.321
Okay. good. Aaron. I'm gonna
want you to be the liaison

74
00:03:18.448 --> 00:03:20.485
between the World Health
Organization and the UN.

75
00:03:20.617 --> 00:03:22.984
We also need to notify the Canadian
and Mexican authorities.

76
00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:26.329
HHS has activated the Strategic National
Stockpile of vaccines and antivirals.

77
00:03:26.456 --> 00:03:28.496
so hopefully one of them
will match this flu strain.

78
00:03:28.625 --> 00:03:29.825
Emily. bring Seth up to speed.

79
00:03:29.918 --> 00:03:32.271
As soon as word leaks out.
panic's gonna spread like wildfire.

80
00:03:32.295 --> 00:03:33.581
- Let's get on it.
- Yes. sir.

81
00:03:36.299 --> 00:03:40.964
100 years ago. the Spanish flu wiped out
5% of the world's population.

82
00:03:41.096 --> 00:03:42.428
How bad is this?

83
00:03:42.556 --> 00:03:44.673
I'll give you a call
when I have boots on the ground.

84
00:03:44.808 --> 00:03:46.015
All right.

85
00:03:48.103 --> 00:03:49.469
Tammy.

86
00:03:51.398 --> 00:03:53.105
Be careful.

87
00:03:53.233 --> 00:03:54.690
Yes. sir.

88
00:04:09.332 --> 00:04:11.039
So I just got off the phone

89
00:04:11.168 --> 00:04:13.660
with an infectious-disease
specialist at the CDC.

90
00:04:13.795 --> 00:04:18.335
This bug is a rapidly mutating pathogen
that accelerates its host's lytic cycle.

91
00:04:18.467 --> 00:04:19.467
English?

92
00:04:19.509 --> 00:04:21.592
Uh. it makes your cells explode.

93
00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:23.962
- Maybe don't tell the press that.
- Yep.

94
00:04:24.848 --> 00:04:27.556
Hey. um. did you leave me
a blueberry muffin?

95
00:04:27.684 --> 00:04:28.720
I did.

96
00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:30.519
That was really nice.

97
00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:33.228
Yeah. I picked out all the blueberries.
so don't make it a big deal.

98
00:04:33.356 --> 00:04:34.722
Well. I won't now.

99
00:04:34.858 --> 00:04:37.566
Oh. uh. that zoologist from
the National Museum wants to come by.

100
00:04:37.694 --> 00:04:40.574
the guy who's naming the animal after
the president. He wants a photo op.

101
00:04:40.697 --> 00:04:43.176
Bringing an alien species into
the White House while we're fighting

102
00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:45.738
a possible pandemic
that originated with animals is...

103
00:04:45.869 --> 00:04:46.869
a great idea.

104
00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:48.406
Hey. I just work here.

105
00:04:48.538 --> 00:04:50.655
Hey. new girl.
You getting up to speed?

106
00:04:50.791 --> 00:04:53.033
Trying. It's a little. uh...

107
00:04:53.168 --> 00:04:54.249
Intimidating?

108
00:04:54.377 --> 00:04:55.584
That's the word.

109
00:04:55.712 --> 00:04:57.419
Just remember
it's another office building.

110
00:04:57.547 --> 00:05:00.585
Whose halls were walked
by Lincoln. FDR and Kennedy.

111
00:05:00.717 --> 00:05:01.958
You'll get used to it.

112
00:05:02.093 --> 00:05:03.550
- Really?
- No.

113
00:05:03.678 --> 00:05:05.385
We're starting you slow. though.

114
00:05:05.514 --> 00:05:07.551
Right. The Emmitt Akin statue.

115
00:05:07.682 --> 00:05:11.050
Yes. a simple Confederate monument
located on federal property.

116
00:05:11.186 --> 00:05:12.722
Some want to keep it.
Some don't.

117
00:05:12.854 --> 00:05:15.221
Well. a federal statue
means federal issue.

118
00:05:15.357 --> 00:05:16.959
This is really important
to the president.

119
00:05:16.983 --> 00:05:19.441
- I thought you were starting me slow.
- That is slow.

120
00:05:19.569 --> 00:05:21.276
How dare you?!
That is racist!

121
00:05:21.404 --> 00:05:23.896
I've been telling you
for an hour. it is not racist!

122
00:05:24.032 --> 00:05:26.069
People. can we just...?

123
00:05:27.869 --> 00:05:28.905
No!

124
00:05:30.413 --> 00:05:33.247
We were making progress here.

125
00:05:34.668 --> 00:05:38.287
Look. Emmitt Akin was
the Mayor of Chattanooga.

126
00:05:38.421 --> 00:05:41.960
He's an historic figure
to many Tennesseans.

127
00:05:42.092 --> 00:05:44.584
That is the Southern Legacy
Foundation's whole point.

128
00:05:44.719 --> 00:05:46.210
He was also a slave holder

129
00:05:46.346 --> 00:05:49.089
who fought to preserve
an oppressive institution.

130
00:05:49.224 --> 00:05:52.092
The erection of his statue
post-Reconstruction

131
00:05:52.227 --> 00:05:54.935
is seen by many
as a monument to Jim Crow.

132
00:05:55.063 --> 00:05:57.503
The statue's smack dab in front
of the old federal courthouse.

133
00:05:57.566 --> 00:05:59.603
It's an official endorsement of racism.

134
00:05:59.734 --> 00:06:01.691
So we've agreed on a middle ground:

135
00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:04.187
to find a less-trafficked area
for the statue

136
00:06:04.322 --> 00:06:08.157
that still honors Tennessee history
while respecting the sensibilities

137
00:06:08.285 --> 00:06:11.153
of those who find it a reminder
of a painful past.

138
00:06:11.288 --> 00:06:14.452
The only party we haven't heard from
is Reverend Dale.

139
00:06:20.672 --> 00:06:24.416
I have spent my life leading protests.

140
00:06:25.468 --> 00:06:29.428
But this issue has caused me
great consternation.

141
00:06:30.307 --> 00:06:32.970
The statue is an emblem

142
00:06:33.101 --> 00:06:36.811
of a dark period in American history.

143
00:06:37.689 --> 00:06:40.306
It enshrines racism.

144
00:06:41.026 --> 00:06:46.647
So it is easy to view it
as a symbol of injustice.

145
00:06:47.657 --> 00:06:50.650
But I see it as a reminder.

146
00:06:51.494 --> 00:06:55.329
and our past must not be... whitewashed.

147
00:06:56.416 --> 00:06:58.783
The statue must not be moved.

148
00:06:58.919 --> 00:07:00.980
- There you go.
- He doesn't want it touched. either!

149
00:07:01.004 --> 00:07:03.462
Have you lost your mind?!

150
00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.343
- It makes no sense.
- Nope.

151
00:07:10.847 --> 00:07:13.555
Lloyd's on the run for six months.
and the last thing he does

152
00:07:13.683 --> 00:07:17.222
before he holes himself up in a bunker
is trash the First Lady's mother's house?

153
00:07:17.354 --> 00:07:18.515
Why?

154
00:07:18.647 --> 00:07:22.357
Because he wanted to show your president
that he could get to his family?

155
00:07:22.484 --> 00:07:27.570
Or - and. uh. just spitballing here -
because he was a psychopath.

156
00:07:27.697 --> 00:07:30.781
Personally. I'm much more interested
in what he was trying to upload.

157
00:07:30.909 --> 00:07:33.868
Look. Lloyd sent that file
across three continents four times

158
00:07:33.995 --> 00:07:37.579
before I located it in a cloud account
on an Australian server.

159
00:07:37.707 --> 00:07:40.700
It's so corrupted that I need to write
a program just to render it.

160
00:07:40.835 --> 00:07:41.871
Yeah.

161
00:07:42.379 --> 00:07:44.496
No problem. Glad you're on it.

162
00:07:44.631 --> 00:07:45.631
Yeah.

163
00:07:45.674 --> 00:07:48.166
So. you must miss London. huh?

164
00:07:48.301 --> 00:07:49.712
Always.

165
00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:53.262
- How long you here for?
- Well. that depends on Hannah.

166
00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:55.723
I can't tell my government
the threat he posed is over

167
00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:57.591
until your government says it is.

168
00:07:57.727 --> 00:08:01.311
And you being the lead investigator.
you're "your government."

169
00:08:01.439 --> 00:08:03.726
My government says to keep digging.

170
00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:07.101
See you later!

171
00:08:08.363 --> 00:08:10.946
Much.

172
00:08:12.951 --> 00:08:15.659
Evidence-response team
tagged everything Lloyd touched.

173
00:08:15.787 --> 00:08:16.948
Why?

174
00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:18.787
He was throwing a tantrum.

175
00:08:21.376 --> 00:08:22.787
What if he wasn't?

176
00:08:22.919 --> 00:08:25.252
<i>Whatever he did.
he always had a method.</i>

177
00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:26.587
<i>Lloyd was meticulous.</i>

178
00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:29.752
He cut a clear pathway
through the house...

179
00:08:30.218 --> 00:08:32.426
and never doubled back.

180
00:08:48.611 --> 00:08:50.611
Every drawer in here is tossed
except for the desk.

181
00:08:50.655 --> 00:08:52.442
Did he run out of time?

182
00:08:52.574 --> 00:08:54.031
Or he wanted to lead us here.

183
00:09:03.918 --> 00:09:06.331
It's a medical record from 1987

184
00:09:06.463 --> 00:09:09.001
for a heart-transplant operation
for Andrew Booker.

185
00:09:09.466 --> 00:09:11.423
That's the First Lady's father.

186
00:09:11.551 --> 00:09:13.884
Why would Mrs. Booker leave
a 30-year-old file

187
00:09:14.012 --> 00:09:16.379
- just randomly lying on top?
- He left it here.

188
00:09:16.514 --> 00:09:19.131
<i>He wasn't looking for something.
He was leaving us something.</i>

189
00:09:19.267 --> 00:09:22.305
But why would he give a toss
about Andrew Booker's heart?

190
00:09:23.021 --> 00:09:25.183
I don't know. But I'm gonna find out.

191
00:09:40.789 --> 00:09:41.789
<i>10 more dead?</i>

192
00:09:41.915 --> 00:09:44.328
<i>And 11 more in the ICU hanging on.</i>

193
00:09:44.459 --> 00:09:47.543
The mortality rate of the patients
in the hospital will be about 40%.

194
00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.832
Have we made any progress?

195
00:09:49.964 --> 00:09:51.000
No.

196
00:09:51.132 --> 00:09:53.089
The viral gestation cycle is short.

197
00:09:53.218 --> 00:09:56.218
<i>The patient's lungs are damaged. and
the oxygen loss leads to organ failure.</i>

198
00:09:56.262 --> 00:09:57.924
What about our antiviral stockpile?

199
00:09:58.056 --> 00:10:00.343
<i>The South Carroll Parish strain
is resistant.</i>

200
00:10:00.475 --> 00:10:02.011
What about creating a new vaccine?

201
00:10:02.143 --> 00:10:05.887
Even if you threw every brain
from the CDC at it. it would take months.

202
00:10:06.022 --> 00:10:07.763
But... I do have an idea.

203
00:10:07.899 --> 00:10:10.767
- We're all ears.
<i>- I read an abstract recently</i>

204
00:10:10.902 --> 00:10:12.859
<i>about an experimental
cancer drug called Extasis</i>

205
00:10:12.987 --> 00:10:14.523
<i>with interesting antiviral properties</i>

206
00:10:14.656 --> 00:10:16.568
<i>that seem to reduce
the ability of viruses</i>

207
00:10:16.699 --> 00:10:19.737
<i>with a genome similar
to the H7N9 to replicate.</i>

208
00:10:19.869 --> 00:10:21.735
So not a prevention but a treatment.

209
00:10:21.871 --> 00:10:23.737
That sounds promising.
Where do we get it?

210
00:10:23.873 --> 00:10:25.205
A guy named Carlton Mackie.

211
00:10:25.333 --> 00:10:28.701
He heads up this cutting-edge pharma firm
in Delaware called Benevax.

212
00:10:28.837 --> 00:10:30.248
- We're on it.
<i>- Meantime.</i>

213
00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:32.963
<i>we need to widen the quarantine
to neighboring counties.</i>

214
00:10:33.091 --> 00:10:34.798
<i>This thing's getting away from us.</i>

215
00:10:39.597 --> 00:10:43.261
What kind of PR bump do you think
the president will get off of an animal?

216
00:10:43.393 --> 00:10:44.554
A small one.

217
00:10:44.686 --> 00:10:46.427
I'd prefer a constellation.

218
00:10:46.563 --> 00:10:49.146
but. uh. this is what you get
when you defund NASA.

219
00:10:49.274 --> 00:10:51.561
I'm gonna ask people to just
keep your voices down

220
00:10:51.693 --> 00:10:54.026
and. please. don't get too close
to the terrarium.

221
00:10:54.154 --> 00:10:58.774
From the Amazonian rainforest.
I present <i>Hylidae kirkmanus.</i>

222
00:11:01.327 --> 00:11:03.489
What is it?
Where is it?

223
00:11:04.539 --> 00:11:07.407
No. no. no. no. no. You can't
name that thing after the president.

224
00:11:07.542 --> 00:11:10.455
- We already have.
- Don't you have something better?

225
00:11:10.587 --> 00:11:13.375
Like a... like a crested eagle
or a panther?

226
00:11:13.506 --> 00:11:15.372
It's not a flea market. Mr. Boone.

227
00:11:15.508 --> 00:11:18.171
Well. see. a flea would be better
'cause then. no one would see it.

228
00:11:18.303 --> 00:11:19.303
- You understand?
- Okay. sorry.

229
00:11:19.304 --> 00:11:21.216
Dr. Chen. I think what Lyor
is trying to say...

230
00:11:21.347 --> 00:11:24.076
- You and Kermit need to leave right now.
- Oh. we can't... Oh. don't...

231
00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:26.203
That's not gonna be possible
'cause it's already travelled

232
00:11:26.227 --> 00:11:29.470
6.000 miles in the last 3 days.
If I move it before it habituates

233
00:11:29.606 --> 00:11:31.446
to its new surroundings;
it could die of shock.

234
00:11:31.566 --> 00:11:33.432
Well. so could the president.

235
00:11:33.568 --> 00:11:35.730
Uh. so... how long. uh.
does he have to stay here?

236
00:11:35.862 --> 00:11:38.650
It's a hermaphrodite.
so it's not a "he."

237
00:11:38.781 --> 00:11:41.615
- Well. this gets better and better.
- Well. I can move it tomorrow.

238
00:11:41.743 --> 00:11:42.904
Great. Thank you so much.

239
00:11:43.036 --> 00:11:44.763
- What about a picture with the president?
- No. no.

240
00:11:44.787 --> 00:11:46.265
We'll see if
he's available in the schedule.

241
00:11:46.289 --> 00:11:48.281
He's not gonna be
available for that ever.

242
00:11:54.797 --> 00:11:57.164
Is Reverend Dale in there?
I was hoping to meet him.

243
00:12:03.348 --> 00:12:04.429
I'll come back.

244
00:12:05.934 --> 00:12:07.971
- Oh. my God!
- Hey.

245
00:12:08.102 --> 00:12:10.219
- How's this thing going?
- Good.

246
00:12:10.355 --> 00:12:12.642
- Screw you!
- Screw you. too!

247
00:12:12.774 --> 00:12:15.562
- Yeah. Sounds good.
- It's a contentious issue.

248
00:12:15.693 --> 00:12:17.150
Do you like frogs?

249
00:12:17.278 --> 00:12:18.278
Frogs?

250
00:12:18.363 --> 00:12:20.229
Exactly. No one does.

251
00:12:20.365 --> 00:12:22.197
So. uh. your thing...

252
00:12:22.325 --> 00:12:23.736
the. uh. Congressional Black Caucus

253
00:12:23.868 --> 00:12:25.971
and civil rights groups are
watching how we handle this.

254
00:12:25.995 --> 00:12:29.204
- A test case. I know. Emily told me.
- Did she mention the dovetailing optics?

255
00:12:29.332 --> 00:12:31.039
- Sorry?
- The outbreak.

256
00:12:31.167 --> 00:12:33.750
South Carroll Parish
is 76% African-American.

257
00:12:33.878 --> 00:12:37.042
So... people of color are dying
in one part of the country

258
00:12:37.173 --> 00:12:39.711
while racist monuments
are protected in another?

259
00:12:39.842 --> 00:12:41.128
<i>No bueno.</i>

260
00:12:41.844 --> 00:12:43.506
- I'm on it.
<i>- You</i> are racist!

261
00:12:43.638 --> 00:12:45.880
- No. <i>you're</i> racist!
- Yeah.

262
00:12:50.061 --> 00:12:51.893
Dr. Bruner is right.

263
00:12:52.021 --> 00:12:54.855
Extasis could work on H7N9.

264
00:12:55.275 --> 00:12:57.733
That's great.
Carlton. that's excellent news.

265
00:12:57.860 --> 00:13:01.399
You're suggesting an un-tested off-label
use not approved by the FDA.

266
00:13:01.531 --> 00:13:03.272
If it doesn't work.
if it kills someone.

267
00:13:03.408 --> 00:13:05.695
Benevax's liability
could be catastrophic.

268
00:13:05.827 --> 00:13:09.696
I understand. which is why I had the
White House counsel's office draw this up.

269
00:13:09.831 --> 00:13:11.117
It's an indemnification.

270
00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:13.707
I appreciate that. Mr. President.

271
00:13:14.711 --> 00:13:16.748
But it will take my lawyers
weeks to vet this.

272
00:13:16.879 --> 00:13:18.165
We don't have weeks.

273
00:13:18.298 --> 00:13:21.962
We... we have hours. People are dying.
Carlton. I'm asking you to trust me.

274
00:13:24.887 --> 00:13:25.887
All due respect. sir.

275
00:13:25.930 --> 00:13:30.391
I have an obligation to my shareholders.
and I don't satisfy that obligation

276
00:13:30.518 --> 00:13:33.010
by saying somebody from
the government said. "Trust me."

277
00:13:34.522 --> 00:13:36.263
Even if that somebody
is the president.

278
00:13:36.399 --> 00:13:39.813
I respect that. Honestly. I-I do.

279
00:13:41.195 --> 00:13:42.811
But there are times in our society

280
00:13:42.947 --> 00:13:46.361
where we have to act in faith
on behalf of the greater good.

281
00:13:46.743 --> 00:13:48.735
And unfortunately.
this is one of them.

282
00:13:52.498 --> 00:13:55.912
I have 10.000 doses
in our Atlanta storage facility.

283
00:13:56.044 --> 00:13:57.910
Which may be enough
to contain this.

284
00:13:58.046 --> 00:13:59.912
I can have HHS
expedite the transfer

285
00:14:00.048 --> 00:14:02.665
- to South Carroll Parish.
- Okay.

286
00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:05.918
Carlton. thank you.
I-I know this isn't easy.

287
00:14:06.387 --> 00:14:07.923
Mr. President.

288
00:14:13.061 --> 00:14:15.804
- He did not look happy.
- No.

289
00:14:15.938 --> 00:14:20.023
Neither do the families in Louisiana
who are burying their loved ones.

290
00:14:22.570 --> 00:14:24.983
The First Lady's father died in 2002.

291
00:14:25.114 --> 00:14:27.322
Why would Lloyd
leave us a breadcrumb trail

292
00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:29.191
to an old medical document?

293
00:14:29.327 --> 00:14:32.866
Because if we find it. it's evidence.
and we're obligated to investigate it.

294
00:14:32.997 --> 00:14:35.831
Evidence of what? And that's
assuming it's not a plant.

295
00:14:35.958 --> 00:14:39.042
There's only one way to find out:
talk to the First Lady.

296
00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:41.332
- What are you gonna tell her?
- As little as possible.

297
00:14:41.464 --> 00:14:44.377
I don't want to drag her into this
if I'm following a Lloyd fabrication.

298
00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:49.970
Okay. so this is an invoice for my mom's
trip down the Danube

299
00:14:50.098 --> 00:14:52.511
with her friend Marlene
a couple years ago.

300
00:14:53.601 --> 00:14:56.059
Another old utility bill.

301
00:14:56.187 --> 00:14:58.304
She stockpiles them.
Don't ask me why.

302
00:14:58.439 --> 00:15:00.772
Agent Wells. is this really necessary?

303
00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:02.641
Yes. ma'am. It is. I'm sorry.

304
00:15:02.777 --> 00:15:05.019
We have to vet everything
that Patrick Lloyd touched.

305
00:15:05.613 --> 00:15:07.229
We need to close the loop.

306
00:15:07.365 --> 00:15:08.606
Wow!

307
00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:10.532
That's weird she kept this.

308
00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:12.151
What is it?

309
00:15:12.286 --> 00:15:15.529
It's the insurance form
for my dad's. um. heart transplant.

310
00:15:15.665 --> 00:15:17.031
He had a transplant?

311
00:15:17.166 --> 00:15:19.874
Yeah. it was one of the first
in the DC area. actually.

312
00:15:20.002 --> 00:15:21.413
I-I was only about 10.

313
00:15:21.546 --> 00:15:23.003
I don't remember a whole lot.

314
00:15:23.131 --> 00:15:26.374
but I-I do remember he was
far down on the recipient list.

315
00:15:26.509 --> 00:15:29.673
and then at the last minute.
you know. it all came together.

316
00:15:30.388 --> 00:15:32.630
- Wow.
- Yeah.

317
00:15:46.821 --> 00:15:47.902
Excuse me.

318
00:15:49.282 --> 00:15:51.023
Did the medication come yet?

319
00:15:54.996 --> 00:15:57.204
Yeah. What? He did what?!

320
00:15:58.875 --> 00:16:00.411
Son of a bitch.

321
00:16:01.335 --> 00:16:03.695
What do you mean Carlton Mackie
didn't deliver the medicine?

322
00:16:03.754 --> 00:16:05.791
He reneged. sir.
He found another buyer.

323
00:16:05.923 --> 00:16:08.415
Pharmacies whose clientele
are willing to pay 2 grand a dose.

324
00:16:08.551 --> 00:16:11.363
So the residents of South Carroll Parish
will not get the medicine they need.

325
00:16:11.387 --> 00:16:13.094
while the residents
in Cameron Parish will.

326
00:16:13.222 --> 00:16:15.325
Yes. sir. It's all about the money;
who has it. who doesn't.

327
00:16:15.349 --> 00:16:17.261
It's like Katrina on steroids.
Mr. President.

328
00:16:17.393 --> 00:16:20.306
Not if I can help it. Tell Kendra I'm
gonna need her in federal court

329
00:16:20.438 --> 00:16:21.929
- as soon as possible.
- Yes. sir.

330
00:16:23.065 --> 00:16:24.681
Yeah. it's the president.

331
00:16:28.529 --> 00:16:30.191
I'm sorry. your honor.

332
00:16:30.323 --> 00:16:32.030
It's your motion. Ms. Daynes.

333
00:16:32.158 --> 00:16:35.196
Yes. for specific enforcement
of a contract.

334
00:16:35.328 --> 00:16:37.240
There's no contract here. judge.

335
00:16:37.371 --> 00:16:39.328
Just a handshake extracted under duress

336
00:16:39.457 --> 00:16:42.950
in the Oval Office
by the leader of the free world.

337
00:16:43.085 --> 00:16:44.576
That's not the contract at issue.

338
00:16:44.712 --> 00:16:47.125
- I'm listening.
- It's a compulsory contract.

339
00:16:47.256 --> 00:16:50.090
The Defense Production Act
requires businesses

340
00:16:50.218 --> 00:16:54.804
essential to the national defense - like
drug manufacturers - to sign agreements

341
00:16:54.931 --> 00:16:56.843
when necessary
for the national defense.

342
00:16:56.974 --> 00:16:58.306
"When necessary."

343
00:16:58.434 --> 00:17:01.802
Mr. Mackie has already made Extasis
available to the population.

344
00:17:01.938 --> 00:17:05.352
To the rich.
And the rich are predominantly white.

345
00:17:05.483 --> 00:17:08.226
Socioeconomic status
is a proxy for race here.

346
00:17:08.361 --> 00:17:10.318
That's not Benevax's concern.

347
00:17:10.446 --> 00:17:11.653
But it's the government's.

348
00:17:11.781 --> 00:17:15.320
South Carroll Parish. a black community.
has 95% of the cases.

349
00:17:15.451 --> 00:17:17.989
The president can decide
how to distribute a drug

350
00:17:18.120 --> 00:17:20.658
during a public health crisis
and at what price.

351
00:17:20.790 --> 00:17:23.954
Why should he be allowed to substitute
his judgment for the private sector's?

352
00:17:24.085 --> 00:17:27.249
Freedom of contract
is a hallmark of our democracy.

353
00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:31.124
But not when the government
is facing down a public-health emergency.

354
00:17:31.259 --> 00:17:36.550
Mr. Mackie. you will relinquish 10.000
doses to the federal government now.

355
00:17:40.601 --> 00:17:41.745
Whoa. this is weird.

356
00:17:41.769 --> 00:17:43.852
What do you have. Chuck?

357
00:17:44.313 --> 00:17:47.522
I rendered the top two inches
of that document Lloyd uploaded.

358
00:17:47.650 --> 00:17:49.391
It's a nine-digit number.

359
00:17:49.527 --> 00:17:51.359
- What's it for?
- No idea.

360
00:17:51.487 --> 00:17:53.854
But you can also make out a date.
June 3. 1987.

361
00:17:53.990 --> 00:17:55.197
1987 again.

362
00:17:55.324 --> 00:17:57.427
That's the year of the First Lady's
father's transplant.

363
00:17:57.451 --> 00:18:00.285
Almost to the day.
The transplant was June the 9th.

364
00:18:00.413 --> 00:18:02.245
That document still
could have been a plant.

365
00:18:02.999 --> 00:18:05.537
Maybe. but it's real.
The First Lady confirmed it.

366
00:18:07.295 --> 00:18:08.706
Chuck. where were...

367
00:18:08.838 --> 00:18:11.125
Bethesda-Sinai's records
pre-2000 haven't been digitized.

368
00:18:11.257 --> 00:18:13.670
The hard copies are
in a storage facility in Virginia.

369
00:18:13.801 --> 00:18:16.259
- I'm texting you guys the address.
- Nice.

370
00:18:16.387 --> 00:18:18.879
See if you can render
the rest of that document.

371
00:18:19.015 --> 00:18:20.631
Yeah. that's the plan.

372
00:18:22.643 --> 00:18:24.009
What's up with you guys?

373
00:18:25.021 --> 00:18:27.229
What? I don't know
what you're talking about.

374
00:18:30.568 --> 00:18:32.685
Hey. I'm hearing
you're a pretty good lawyer.

375
00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:34.106
Thanks. It... It went well.

376
00:18:34.238 --> 00:18:36.195
- Good. And the statue thing?
- Um...

377
00:18:36.324 --> 00:18:37.906
- You're killing it. right?
- Right.

378
00:18:38.034 --> 00:18:41.027
Good. Because we are un-conquerable.
The <i>crème de la crème.</i>

379
00:18:41.162 --> 00:18:42.949
The <i>ne plus ultra.</i>

380
00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:44.787
- Kendra?
- Yes?

381
00:18:44.915 --> 00:18:47.874
- That door.
- Right.

382
00:18:48.002 --> 00:18:49.994
Thanks.

383
00:18:51.339 --> 00:18:52.625
Come on. stop with that!

384
00:18:54.842 --> 00:18:58.256
The proposal on the table
is a compromise solution.

385
00:18:58.387 --> 00:19:00.800
The statue will be moved
from the courthouse

386
00:19:00.931 --> 00:19:03.218
to the Chickamauga National Forest.

387
00:19:04.852 --> 00:19:06.263
Reverend Dale?

388
00:19:07.355 --> 00:19:11.395
I appreciate your efforts
at conciliation. Ms. Daynes.

389
00:19:11.525 --> 00:19:14.939
But I still remain
fundamentally opposed

390
00:19:15.071 --> 00:19:17.188
to the relocation of that statue.

391
00:19:18.949 --> 00:19:21.987
At least we know the price
for the great Tramer Dale selling out.

392
00:19:23.204 --> 00:19:25.070
A trip to the White House.

393
00:19:25.790 --> 00:19:27.122
Young lady...

394
00:19:27.917 --> 00:19:29.499
you mean well.

395
00:19:30.294 --> 00:19:34.629
You declare this is racist
and that is racist.

396
00:19:34.757 --> 00:19:38.922
But you are young. white.
and living in America.

397
00:19:39.929 --> 00:19:42.888
You don't know what it's like
to walk in my shoes.

398
00:19:43.641 --> 00:19:46.429
And I won't always be around to tell you.

399
00:19:47.436 --> 00:19:49.928
but that statue will.

400
00:19:51.649 --> 00:19:53.515
It stays.

401
00:19:56.904 --> 00:19:58.645
How's it going down there?

402
00:19:58.781 --> 00:20:00.647
<i>The drugs arrived
late this afternoon.</i>

403
00:20:00.783 --> 00:20:03.821
My team spent the rest of the day
titrating the proper dose.

404
00:20:03.953 --> 00:20:05.660
You think it's gonna work?

405
00:20:05.788 --> 00:20:08.701
<i>I don't know. sir.
We're administering it now.</i>

406
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:11.787
I don't even have the words.

407
00:20:12.461 --> 00:20:13.668
Sir?

408
00:20:13.796 --> 00:20:16.129
To tell you how grateful I am.

409
00:20:17.133 --> 00:20:20.126
The greatest enemy we face
these days is one we can't even see.

410
00:20:20.261 --> 00:20:22.594
and I send you down there
behind enemy lines.

411
00:20:22.722 --> 00:20:23.963
<i>And you go.</i>

412
00:20:24.098 --> 00:20:27.466
Without hesitation.
no questions asked.

413
00:20:27.935 --> 00:20:29.892
Do you know why I do it?

414
00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:31.136
<i>Why?</i>

415
00:20:32.148 --> 00:20:33.684
Because I know that you would.

416
00:20:36.068 --> 00:20:38.811
<i>- I'll update you in the morning.</i>
- Thanks. Tammy.

417
00:20:41.157 --> 00:20:42.648
Bye.

418
00:20:59.925 --> 00:21:02.087
I already reconnoitered the place.

419
00:21:02.219 --> 00:21:04.711
Crap security. and no one on site.

420
00:21:05.973 --> 00:21:07.893
You sure you don't want
to go the subpoena route?

421
00:21:08.017 --> 00:21:09.553
Well. they're medical records.

422
00:21:09.685 --> 00:21:12.098
It would take months to get through
the HIPAA regulations.

423
00:21:12.229 --> 00:21:14.846
The enduring charm
of American bureaucracy.

424
00:21:15.983 --> 00:21:18.441
Let's head around back.
I cut a hole in the fence.

425
00:21:19.528 --> 00:21:20.860
Oh. subpoena. huh?

426
00:21:20.988 --> 00:21:22.980
I didn't say <i>I</i> needed one.

427
00:21:26.535 --> 00:21:28.492
We should find the main office.

428
00:21:28.621 --> 00:21:30.954
There's got to be a computer here
with a directory.

429
00:21:31.081 --> 00:21:32.197
It's alphabetized.

430
00:21:32.333 --> 00:21:34.040
Floors are organized
by month and year.

431
00:21:38.255 --> 00:21:40.087
Is that a light on?

432
00:21:41.801 --> 00:21:42.917
Hannah!

433
00:22:20.422 --> 00:22:23.401
Do you guys want to tell me what you're
doing on private property after hours?

434
00:22:23.425 --> 00:22:24.541
No.

435
00:22:25.052 --> 00:22:26.293
Want to start again?

436
00:22:26.428 --> 00:22:28.920
'Cause right now I got you
on B&E and torching the place.

437
00:22:29.765 --> 00:22:31.882
That supposed to impress me.
Agent Wells?

438
00:22:32.017 --> 00:22:34.579
No. it's just to show you that
we're working a federal investigation

439
00:22:34.603 --> 00:22:36.765
and that I don't have to answer
any of your questions.

440
00:22:36.897 --> 00:22:38.263
Well. this isn't federal property.

441
00:22:38.399 --> 00:22:39.685
Well. <i>I</i> am.

442
00:22:39.817 --> 00:22:41.777
So call the White House
and verify my credentials.

443
00:22:44.446 --> 00:22:47.029
I'm still gonna need a statement
from both of you.

444
00:22:47.157 --> 00:22:48.773
We'll send one over.

445
00:22:50.619 --> 00:22:52.736
- You good?
- Yeah.

446
00:22:53.789 --> 00:22:57.499
Hanging around with you
should qualify me for hazard pay.

447
00:22:57.626 --> 00:23:00.289
I've been shot. knocked unconscious.

448
00:23:00.421 --> 00:23:02.128
Not stabbed. though.

449
00:23:02.256 --> 00:23:04.623
No. not yet.

450
00:23:06.468 --> 00:23:07.959
As of 8:00 a.m..

451
00:23:08.095 --> 00:23:10.838
we have a total of 74 fatalities
attributed to the virus.

452
00:23:10.973 --> 00:23:13.681
There are 64 in South Carroll Parish.

453
00:23:13.809 --> 00:23:17.974
8 in Cameron Parish.
and 2 in Wilkinson County. Mississippi.

454
00:23:18.105 --> 00:23:20.347
It spread to Mississippi?

455
00:23:20.482 --> 00:23:23.395
Yes. we have a small cluster
of cases in Mississippi and Texas.

456
00:23:23.527 --> 00:23:24.727
So it's a full-blown epidemic.

457
00:23:24.778 --> 00:23:27.486
No. According to CDC parameters.
this is still a localized outbreak.

458
00:23:27.615 --> 00:23:28.856
That crossed state lines.

459
00:23:28.991 --> 00:23:30.711
That the federal government.
in concert with

460
00:23:30.784 --> 00:23:33.117
local and state authorities.
is aggressively containing.

461
00:23:34.538 --> 00:23:36.621
- Seth's good.
- Yep.

462
00:23:36.749 --> 00:23:38.536
- The virus is better.
- Yep.

463
00:23:38.667 --> 00:23:40.875
The NAACP wants to know
why eight times as many people

464
00:23:41.003 --> 00:23:43.165
have died in a black parish
than a white parish.

465
00:23:43.297 --> 00:23:44.879
That's a fair question.

466
00:23:45.007 --> 00:23:46.818
I'm saying the president needs
to devote more resources...

467
00:23:46.842 --> 00:23:49.380
Look. we have the CDC. HHS.
NIH. FEMA...

468
00:23:49.511 --> 00:23:52.003
I don't think we can contain this
with acronyms. Emily.

469
00:23:52.681 --> 00:23:55.424
Good morning. doc.
Did you get any sleep?

470
00:23:55.559 --> 00:23:57.095
<i>No. sir. You?</i>

471
00:23:57.227 --> 00:24:00.140
No. not really.
How are we doing?

472
00:24:00.272 --> 00:24:01.392
The Extasis is working. sir.

473
00:24:01.523 --> 00:24:03.059
It dramatically reduces
the viral load

474
00:24:03.192 --> 00:24:05.479
so that the body's immune system
has a fighting chance.

475
00:24:05.611 --> 00:24:08.524
<i>The patients that we've
administered it to are recovering.</i>

476
00:24:08.656 --> 00:24:09.656
Thank God.

477
00:24:09.698 --> 00:24:11.280
The problem is we don't have enough.

478
00:24:11.408 --> 00:24:13.695
<i>- Not anymore.</i>
- Well. we lost a lot of time.

479
00:24:13.827 --> 00:24:16.035
We had to chase
that son of a bitch into court.

480
00:24:16.163 --> 00:24:19.247
<i>Yes. sir. and this virus is moving
much faster than we thought.</i>

481
00:24:19.375 --> 00:24:20.911
<i>We need more medicine.</i>

482
00:24:21.043 --> 00:24:23.330
Unfortunately. Mackie gave us
everything that he had.

483
00:24:23.462 --> 00:24:26.455
<i>- 10.000 doses. right?</i>
- That's correct.

484
00:24:26.590 --> 00:24:29.628
<i>- I don't think that's all he had.</i>
- Why?

485
00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:32.047
<i>This medication is
extremely expensive to develop.</i>

486
00:24:32.179 --> 00:24:35.798
<i>10.000 doses is simply not
a cost-effective production.</i>

487
00:24:35.933 --> 00:24:39.267
<i>especially for a company that invests
as much into R&D as Benevax.</i>

488
00:24:39.395 --> 00:24:43.389
Right. We'll look into it. I'll get
back to you as soon as we can.

489
00:24:43.941 --> 00:24:45.398
- Emily. I want...
- On it. sir.

490
00:24:52.783 --> 00:24:55.241
So this is the famous Kirkman toad?

491
00:24:55.369 --> 00:24:58.203
South American tree frog? Yes.

492
00:24:58.872 --> 00:25:02.331
Yeah. it's not a particularly robust
example of the genus.

493
00:25:02.459 --> 00:25:05.918
I don't think you're qualified
to opine about its robustness.

494
00:25:06.714 --> 00:25:07.955
It's spindly.

495
00:25:12.219 --> 00:25:13.755
And now it's <i>not</i> spindly.

496
00:25:14.263 --> 00:25:15.549
It's a fight-or-flight response.

497
00:25:15.681 --> 00:25:18.094
Maybe if you stop staring at it...

498
00:25:18.225 --> 00:25:21.138
I don't think it's smart enough
to view me as a threat.

499
00:25:21.270 --> 00:25:24.070
Yeah. brain-to-body mass. frogs are
very low on the evolutionary scale.

500
00:25:24.189 --> 00:25:27.808
They're stupid. even by the modest
standards of amphibians.

501
00:25:27.943 --> 00:25:29.775
Do you need to be here?

502
00:25:29.903 --> 00:25:31.644
Tasty. though. Yeah.

503
00:25:31.780 --> 00:25:35.490
I sampled the related frog.
xenopus levis. on safari in Angola.

504
00:25:35.617 --> 00:25:37.609
And I must tell you...

505
00:25:38.287 --> 00:25:40.370
they go wonderfully with tamarind.

506
00:25:40.998 --> 00:25:44.332
- You're a total disgrace.
- Excuse me. Kendra.

507
00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:48.374
The Congressional Black Caucus wants
an update on the statue negotiations.

508
00:25:48.505 --> 00:25:49.996
Update.

509
00:25:50.132 --> 00:25:51.623
Right.

510
00:25:56.722 --> 00:25:59.009
Lyor. can I borrow you
for a minute?

511
00:26:01.351 --> 00:26:03.183
I'm just offering
another perspective.

512
00:26:03.312 --> 00:26:06.180
By accusing us all
of profiting from slavery?

513
00:26:06.315 --> 00:26:07.556
Well. you have.

514
00:26:07.691 --> 00:26:08.852
- Richly.
- How dare you!

515
00:26:09.651 --> 00:26:11.517
You... you and
the Progressive Committee.

516
00:26:11.653 --> 00:26:14.507
you wouldn't be in business without the
historic oppression of African Americans.

517
00:26:14.531 --> 00:26:16.523
- You'd be saving the whales.
- That's slander.

518
00:26:16.658 --> 00:26:19.617
And. Reverend Dale. I've admired you
since reading <i>Hear the Trumpets Blow.</i>

519
00:26:19.745 --> 00:26:22.488
but without slavery. you're preaching
in a one-room church

520
00:26:22.623 --> 00:26:24.463
and selling raffle tickets
to keep the heat on.

521
00:26:24.500 --> 00:26:27.459
- Let me tell you something. son...
- And the Southern Legacy Foundation?

522
00:26:27.586 --> 00:26:29.543
Well... "Southern Legacy."

523
00:26:29.671 --> 00:26:31.879
Who the hell do you think you are?

524
00:26:32.007 --> 00:26:35.216
A cynical and sad human being.

525
00:26:35.844 --> 00:26:39.463
And I am not prepared
to continue with him in the room.

526
00:26:39.598 --> 00:26:41.464
- Get him out of here!
- That's right.

527
00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:44.308
Please. just get him out of here!

528
00:26:45.687 --> 00:26:47.599
- Thank you. Lyor.
- You're welcome.

529
00:26:47.731 --> 00:26:50.223
Did you and Damian
break into a storage unit?

530
00:26:50.359 --> 00:26:52.519
We were following up on a lead
regarding Patrick Lloyd.

531
00:26:52.569 --> 00:26:53.810
With a burglary.

532
00:26:53.946 --> 00:26:56.063
Aaron. I can't get into the details.

533
00:26:56.198 --> 00:26:57.905
Hannah. you answer to me.

534
00:26:58.033 --> 00:26:59.774
And you answer to the president.

535
00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:03.074
- Your point being...?
- That this is about his family.

536
00:27:03.205 --> 00:27:05.538
And until I know
exactly what I'm dealing with...

537
00:27:05.666 --> 00:27:08.534
- You don't want to expose me.
- Yeah.

538
00:27:10.379 --> 00:27:11.379
Okay.

539
00:27:12.798 --> 00:27:14.255
All right.

540
00:27:14.383 --> 00:27:16.875
I'll trust you on this. Hannah.
and I'll run interference.

541
00:27:17.010 --> 00:27:18.876
but what I can't do
is run interference

542
00:27:19.012 --> 00:27:20.772
for someone who works
for another government.

543
00:27:21.723 --> 00:27:24.056
Surveillance cameras
on the factory across the street

544
00:27:24.184 --> 00:27:26.050
caught him breaking through that fence.

545
00:27:26.562 --> 00:27:28.975
He can answer for that. or he can leave.

546
00:27:29.106 --> 00:27:31.564
All right. I'll tell him.

547
00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:38.693
Reverend Dale.
this is a great honor for me.

548
00:27:38.824 --> 00:27:40.281
The honor is mine. sir.

549
00:27:40.409 --> 00:27:42.321
I also wanted to thank you

550
00:27:42.452 --> 00:27:44.944
for your willingness
to compromise on the statue.

551
00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:48.289
In the end. we moved it to an area
that was less trafficked.

552
00:27:48.417 --> 00:27:50.409
I know that's not what you wanted.

553
00:27:50.544 --> 00:27:54.003
No. sir. I believe we sanitize history
at our peril.

554
00:27:54.131 --> 00:27:56.919
It's nice when it's history we don't like.

555
00:27:57.050 --> 00:28:00.214
- But not when it's something we do.
- Yes. sir.

556
00:28:00.345 --> 00:28:03.008
It's a dangerous precedent
we set here today. sir.

557
00:28:03.140 --> 00:28:05.223
I don't disagree with you.
but sometimes.

558
00:28:05.350 --> 00:28:08.309
compromise seems to be
the only way to move forward.

559
00:28:08.437 --> 00:28:09.473
Yeah.

560
00:28:09.605 --> 00:28:12.268
Well. you can thank your pistol
of a young lawyer here

561
00:28:12.399 --> 00:28:14.391
for bringing me around.

562
00:28:15.402 --> 00:28:19.612
She reminded me that
there's no virtue in absolutism.

563
00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:23.153
Old lions like me can be stubborn.

564
00:28:23.952 --> 00:28:25.944
Yet they still roar.

565
00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:29.788
- Mr. President.
- Reverend. please.

566
00:28:31.084 --> 00:28:33.952
Reverend Dale.
may I lead you out. sir?

567
00:28:34.630 --> 00:28:36.792
No. But you may walk <i>with</i> me.

568
00:28:41.178 --> 00:28:42.760
How'd you turn them around?

569
00:28:42.888 --> 00:28:47.679
I unified them by giving them
a common figure to hate.

570
00:28:47.809 --> 00:28:48.845
Huh.

571
00:28:48.977 --> 00:28:51.060
Sadly. I'm starting to realize that

572
00:28:51.188 --> 00:28:54.147
that's one of the great secrets
of good governance.

573
00:28:54.816 --> 00:28:58.605
Sir. Carlton Mackie's in the West Wing.
Want me to bring him in?

574
00:28:58.737 --> 00:29:01.980
No. he doesn't set foot
in the Oval Office ever again.

575
00:29:02.783 --> 00:29:04.194
Excuse me.

576
00:29:08.205 --> 00:29:09.616
You recognize this?

577
00:29:09.748 --> 00:29:12.161
It's a bill of lading from
the United States Postal Service

578
00:29:12.292 --> 00:29:16.662
for the shipment of 30.000 doses of
Extasis to a warehouse in Jacksonville.

579
00:29:16.797 --> 00:29:18.538
You're in violation of a court order.

580
00:29:18.674 --> 00:29:21.166
No. sir. Court order covered
exactly 10.000 doses.

581
00:29:21.301 --> 00:29:22.587
Because you misled us.

582
00:29:22.719 --> 00:29:24.836
You allowed us to believe
that's all you had.

583
00:29:24.972 --> 00:29:27.180
You failed to acknowledge
the 30.000 doses

584
00:29:27.307 --> 00:29:28.889
that you were holding in reserve.

585
00:29:29.017 --> 00:29:30.883
I provided an amount
I was told was sufficient.

586
00:29:31.019 --> 00:29:34.353
Which very well might have been if
we didn't have to hunt you down to get it.

587
00:29:34.481 --> 00:29:36.097
Lives are at stake here. Mr. Mackie.

588
00:29:36.233 --> 00:29:37.565
I understand that.

589
00:29:37.693 --> 00:29:39.901
which is why I'm making
additional doses available.

590
00:29:40.028 --> 00:29:42.111
So you and your company
can line your pockets.

591
00:29:42.239 --> 00:29:44.196
Respectfully. sir.
it is not that simple.

592
00:29:44.324 --> 00:29:47.738
Extasis is an experimental drug.
Our patent is pending.

593
00:29:47.869 --> 00:29:49.826
But now the drug is in circulation.

594
00:29:49.955 --> 00:29:52.743
meaning every lab in America
will be reverse-engineering it by Monday.

595
00:29:52.874 --> 00:29:55.082
We spent 1 billion
in R&D on this drug.

596
00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:57.793
If that investment is gone.
so is my company.

597
00:29:57.921 --> 00:29:59.457
That is absolutely ridiculous.

598
00:29:59.589 --> 00:30:02.332
You're gonna peddle some kind of
corporate doomsday scenario

599
00:30:02.467 --> 00:30:04.379
while the country
is really dealing with one?!

600
00:30:04.511 --> 00:30:06.377
Pharmaceutical companies
have made billions

601
00:30:06.513 --> 00:30:10.052
upon billions of dollars profit every
year on the backs of the American people

602
00:30:10.183 --> 00:30:12.391
with the understanding
that if there is ever a crisis -

603
00:30:12.519 --> 00:30:15.227
a <i>real</i> emergency -
you people would finally step up

604
00:30:15.355 --> 00:30:17.813
and do the right thing
and make a sacrifice!

605
00:30:17.941 --> 00:30:19.807
It isn't just my sacrifice.

606
00:30:19.943 --> 00:30:22.731
We have heart-disease drugs
in the pipeline. diabetes drugs.

607
00:30:22.863 --> 00:30:25.150
Whatever happens with this outbreak.
if we go bankrupt.

608
00:30:25.282 --> 00:30:29.071
more people will die from the drugs that
we do not develop than from this bug.

609
00:30:29.202 --> 00:30:31.785
I took an oath
to protect the American people.

610
00:30:31.913 --> 00:30:35.782
My job is to save lives now. today.
and I will not let you get in the way.

611
00:30:35.917 --> 00:30:37.658
I know what you think of me. sir.

612
00:30:37.794 --> 00:30:39.831
but I'm not a racist;
I'm a capitalist.

613
00:30:39.963 --> 00:30:44.253
Yet the fact still remains the community
that is suffering from this right now...

614
00:30:46.261 --> 00:30:48.127
...is made up of minorities.

615
00:30:48.263 --> 00:30:51.597
And I want to help them.
But I don't run a charity.

616
00:30:51.725 --> 00:30:53.557
So pay me what I deserve

617
00:30:53.685 --> 00:30:55.325
or have me arrested
for contempt of court.

618
00:30:55.395 --> 00:30:57.808
but your lawyers
better be ready for a fight.

619
00:30:57.939 --> 00:31:01.432
In the meantime. Mr. President.
I have a business to run.

620
00:31:03.779 --> 00:31:05.111
Just like you.

621
00:31:11.912 --> 00:31:14.996
He's got us. sir. By the time we get
our hands on his supply.

622
00:31:15.123 --> 00:31:16.955
it'll be a drop in the bucket.

623
00:31:23.131 --> 00:31:24.997
Get me Reverend Dale.

624
00:31:25.133 --> 00:31:27.591
See if the old lion
has one roar left in him.

625
00:31:30.263 --> 00:31:32.801
Equal treatment for all people.

626
00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:37.139
A principle for which
so many have fought and died.

627
00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:40.388
But Carlton Mackie
doesn't believe in that.

628
00:31:40.524 --> 00:31:42.186
He believes only the rich

629
00:31:42.317 --> 00:31:45.185
should benefit from the healing powers
of modern medicine.

630
00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:48.358
<i>The rest of us can be left
to sicken and die.</i>

631
00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:51.983
<i>Like the good people
of South Carroll Parish.</i>

632
00:31:53.161 --> 00:31:55.824
- Do you know what you've done?
- Yes.

633
00:31:56.206 --> 00:31:58.368
I've ruined your reputation.

634
00:31:58.500 --> 00:32:01.618
But I'm gonna give you a chance
to get it back.

635
00:32:02.045 --> 00:32:03.877
Today. Carlton Mackie
will be providing

636
00:32:04.005 --> 00:32:07.089
Benevax's entire stockpile
of Extasis to the government.

637
00:32:07.217 --> 00:32:10.801
And a grateful nation is in his debt.

638
00:32:10.929 --> 00:32:15.014
To me. this is not just
responsible corporate citizenship.

639
00:32:15.142 --> 00:32:19.603
This is what it means to be
an American - a great American.

640
00:32:19.729 --> 00:32:22.062
Ladies and gentlemen.
members of the press.

641
00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:25.433
it is my privilege
to introduce Carlton Mackie.

642
00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:31.273
The most powerful man in the world
sucking up to the guy

643
00:32:31.408 --> 00:32:33.570
who lied to his face
and tried to shake him down.

644
00:32:33.702 --> 00:32:36.410
- You know what you call that?
- Leadership.

645
00:32:36.538 --> 00:32:38.120
Damn straight.

646
00:32:38.248 --> 00:32:40.490
Thank you.

647
00:32:40.625 --> 00:32:44.209
One-way ticket and 12 hours
to leave the country?

648
00:32:44.337 --> 00:32:47.045
Your government's pretty ungrateful.

649
00:32:47.174 --> 00:32:50.758
Yeah. in England.
you'd get a-a ceremony. right?

650
00:32:50.886 --> 00:32:52.969
In England. I'd be knighted.

651
00:32:53.096 --> 00:32:55.509
Well. we don't think much
of burglars here. I guess.

652
00:32:55.640 --> 00:32:59.099
Yeah. well. I don't think much
of not finishing a job.

653
00:32:59.227 --> 00:33:01.059
I'll keep you posted. Don't worry.

654
00:33:04.191 --> 00:33:05.398
Wells.

655
00:33:05.525 --> 00:33:07.391
No. I'm gonna walk you out.

656
00:33:09.029 --> 00:33:10.691
I'm touched.

657
00:33:10.822 --> 00:33:12.108
Don't be.

658
00:33:12.240 --> 00:33:14.402
They wanted me to make sure
you got in the cab.

659
00:33:16.703 --> 00:33:18.069
Charles.

660
00:33:19.247 --> 00:33:20.704
Cheerio. mate.

661
00:33:26.671 --> 00:33:27.957
Hey. slow down.

662
00:33:28.089 --> 00:33:31.002
24 hours on the button.
If that thing's still here.

663
00:33:31.134 --> 00:33:33.626
I'm gonna frog-walk it
down Pennsylvania Avenue myself.

664
00:33:33.762 --> 00:33:34.843
That's a little harsh.

665
00:33:34.971 --> 00:33:38.806
Well. you want to write a release
about a swollen. sexually ambiguous toad

666
00:33:38.934 --> 00:33:41.370
named after the president. whose
defining characteristic. by the way.

667
00:33:41.394 --> 00:33:43.727
is that it expectorates
on its insect prey?

668
00:33:44.397 --> 00:33:45.933
Not so much.

669
00:33:48.652 --> 00:33:50.268
Hey.

670
00:33:50.403 --> 00:33:53.692
Dr. Chen was just filling me in
on our little friend here.

671
00:33:53.823 --> 00:33:54.782
Yes. indeed.

672
00:33:54.783 --> 00:33:56.570
He's incredibly resilient.

673
00:33:56.701 --> 00:34:00.035
Can fight off a wide variety of enemies.
holds his ground.

674
00:34:00.163 --> 00:34:01.995
It's fiercely protective
of its family.

675
00:34:02.123 --> 00:34:04.477
And doesn't even sleep much.
I think he's a perfect namesake.

676
00:34:04.501 --> 00:34:06.117
We thought so too. sir.

677
00:34:06.253 --> 00:34:08.461
Seth. why don't you get
the White House photographer?

678
00:34:08.588 --> 00:34:11.626
<i>Hylidae kirkmanus</i> is ready
for his close-up.

679
00:34:12.467 --> 00:34:14.675
Yes.
While we're young. Seth.

680
00:34:14.803 --> 00:34:17.466
America's waiting.

681
00:34:21.142 --> 00:34:23.179
Just beautiful.

682
00:34:26.106 --> 00:34:28.143
A defense-department
purchase order.

683
00:34:28.275 --> 00:34:30.115
Yeah. for a contractor
called Icarus Astrotech.

684
00:34:30.235 --> 00:34:33.148
First Lady mentioned that her mother
was a government secretary.

685
00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:34.487
- Where did she work?
- D.O.D.

686
00:34:34.614 --> 00:34:36.025
Contract Oversight Services.

687
00:34:36.157 --> 00:34:38.194
Her department would have
handled Icarus bids.

688
00:34:38.326 --> 00:34:39.988
And which Icarus employee signed this?

689
00:34:41.371 --> 00:34:43.829
Contracts officer named Eric Little.

690
00:34:43.957 --> 00:34:45.539
Still works there. actually.

691
00:34:45.667 --> 00:34:48.705
So the First Lady's dad
gets a heart transplant

692
00:34:49.713 --> 00:34:51.204
around the same time
that her mother

693
00:34:51.339 --> 00:34:54.298
is handling the paperwork
for a defense contract.

694
00:34:55.302 --> 00:34:58.010
Why does Patrick Lloyd
want us to know this?

695
00:35:01.433 --> 00:35:02.640
Chuck...?

696
00:35:02.767 --> 00:35:05.680
Look. there's a difference between
correlation and coincidence.

697
00:35:05.812 --> 00:35:07.724
Tell me what you correlated.

698
00:35:09.816 --> 00:35:13.400
I looked into Eric Little. In 1987.
he was on the board of the hospital

699
00:35:13.528 --> 00:35:15.110
where Alex's dad got his transplant.

700
00:35:15.238 --> 00:35:17.855
- A bribe?
- If you're reaching. yeah.

701
00:35:17.991 --> 00:35:19.778
So let's play this out.

702
00:35:19.909 --> 00:35:22.242
The First Lady's mother
gives inside info

703
00:35:22.370 --> 00:35:25.283
to a government contractor
in order to win a bid.

704
00:35:25.415 --> 00:35:28.533
So the First Lady's father
could move up the transplant list?

705
00:35:30.170 --> 00:35:32.457
It's a pretty circumstantial case.

706
00:35:32.589 --> 00:35:34.626
Which is why we need
to speak to Eric Little.

707
00:35:37.135 --> 00:35:39.548
Eric Little's address.
Reston. Virginia.

708
00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:44.636
Hey.

709
00:35:45.602 --> 00:35:46.934
You coming?

710
00:35:52.776 --> 00:35:54.642
Tammy. it's Tom.
Can you hear me?

711
00:35:54.778 --> 00:35:56.895
<i>We got the rest
of the medication. sir.</i>

712
00:35:57.030 --> 00:36:00.740
<i>- We're administering it as we speak.</i>
- Is it working?

713
00:36:00.867 --> 00:36:03.484
<i>I think we might have
this bastard on the run.</i>

714
00:36:03.620 --> 00:36:05.452
That is fantastic news.

715
00:36:06.247 --> 00:36:09.706
- Your country owes you a great debt.
<i>- Notjust me. sir.</i>

716
00:36:09.834 --> 00:36:11.075
All of us.

717
00:36:11.211 --> 00:36:14.204
The doctors and the nurses
and all the volunteers

718
00:36:14.339 --> 00:36:17.958
who've stayed up for 48 hours
trying to beat this thing.

719
00:36:18.426 --> 00:36:20.292
Tammy. what's wrong?
You don't look well.

720
00:36:20.428 --> 00:36:23.171
- It's not what you think.
- What is it?

721
00:36:23.890 --> 00:36:26.633
- It's kidney failure.
<i>- What?</i>

722
00:36:26.768 --> 00:36:27.804
How?

723
00:36:28.895 --> 00:36:32.980
<i>I had to test out the antiviral on myself
to determine its toxicity.</i>

724
00:36:33.108 --> 00:36:35.566
<i>and I knew the quickest way to do it.</i>

725
00:36:36.111 --> 00:36:39.980
<i>Turns out the proper dosage
is only one milliliter. not two.</i>

726
00:36:40.115 --> 00:36:42.555
I want you out of there.
I'm bringing you back to Walter Reed.

727
00:36:42.659 --> 00:36:44.696
<i>- You're coming home.</i>
- No. Mr. President.

728
00:36:44.828 --> 00:36:46.490
- I'm not asking.
<i>- I know. sir.</i>

729
00:36:46.621 --> 00:36:48.658
But we're still fighting here.

730
00:36:49.249 --> 00:36:52.708
A good soldier
doesn't leave the field early.

731
00:36:52.836 --> 00:36:55.453
She stays until the last shot is fired.

732
00:36:57.006 --> 00:36:58.292
It's what you would do.

733
00:36:58.425 --> 00:37:01.133
- You told me yourself...
<i>- I have to see this through. sir.</i>

734
00:37:03.138 --> 00:37:04.800
I'll check in with you in the morning.

735
00:37:14.357 --> 00:37:17.691
Two Air Force muscleheads
are telling me I got to get on a plane.

736
00:37:17.819 --> 00:37:21.813
that they're gonna carry me out
if I resist. That's called kidnapping.

737
00:37:21.948 --> 00:37:24.986
Well. you're gonna have to
take that up with a higher authority.

738
00:37:25.493 --> 00:37:28.361
Wait a second.
I <i>am</i> the higher authority.

739
00:37:28.496 --> 00:37:31.216
Come on. Tammy. They were following
orders. They were trying to help.

740
00:37:31.332 --> 00:37:32.368
Yeah. I suppose.

741
00:37:32.500 --> 00:37:34.708
The doc says you're gonna make
a full recovery.

742
00:37:37.505 --> 00:37:39.497
I didn't get the job done.

743
00:37:40.258 --> 00:37:44.377
I am a soldier who left the field
of battle before the battle was won.

744
00:37:44.512 --> 00:37:45.878
Think of it like this.

745
00:37:46.014 --> 00:37:48.882
I'm a general who refuses
to leave anyone behind.

746
00:37:49.017 --> 00:37:50.553
and I outrank you.

747
00:37:54.189 --> 00:37:56.522
Now. I want you
to behave yourself.

748
00:37:58.359 --> 00:38:00.396
Listen to the nurses
and do what they tell you

749
00:38:00.528 --> 00:38:03.942
because if I have to come back.
it is not going to be pretty.

750
00:38:04.532 --> 00:38:05.989
Yes. sir.

751
00:38:10.371 --> 00:38:12.363
She's gonna need
some more Jell-O.

752
00:38:20.173 --> 00:38:21.414
Looks about right.

753
00:38:21.549 --> 00:38:23.916
I hear you're off
to a pretty good start.

754
00:38:24.052 --> 00:38:26.214
Oh. no. I guess.
Maybe I'm just off.

755
00:38:26.346 --> 00:38:29.259
You negotiated a settlement
for the Emmitt Akin statue.

756
00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:31.302
That no one's really happy with.

757
00:38:31.434 --> 00:38:34.518
You went to court to get medicine
distributed to sick people.

758
00:38:34.646 --> 00:38:36.057
A bunch of whom died

759
00:38:36.189 --> 00:38:39.057
because we didn't
get it there fast enough.

760
00:38:39.192 --> 00:38:41.980
See. firing on all cylinders.

761
00:38:42.111 --> 00:38:45.070
Feels like the whole job around here
is just putting out fires.

762
00:38:45.198 --> 00:38:46.734
Is it always like this?

763
00:38:47.408 --> 00:38:48.569
No.

764
00:38:48.701 --> 00:38:50.738
Usually. the flames are much higher.

765
00:38:56.709 --> 00:38:59.247
Did you get a chance
to talk to the reverend?

766
00:38:59.379 --> 00:39:01.917
Yes. sir. And I shook his hand.

767
00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:05.128
It's one of the many things
I'll get to tell my grandchildren.

768
00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:08.298
He's seen so much.

769
00:39:08.429 --> 00:39:13.345
I can't help but wonder what
he honestly thinks about where we are.

770
00:39:13.476 --> 00:39:15.058
What about you. Mike?

771
00:39:15.812 --> 00:39:17.804
What do you think
about where we are?

772
00:39:20.441 --> 00:39:24.606
Sir. this country's constitution
originally said I was 3/5 of a person.

773
00:39:25.697 --> 00:39:27.404
That's where we started.

774
00:39:28.074 --> 00:39:30.282
But I'm more interested
in where we're headed.

775
00:39:31.619 --> 00:39:34.282
- We need to do better.
- Yeah.

776
00:39:35.456 --> 00:39:37.243
But we've also come a long way.

777
00:39:37.375 --> 00:39:39.788
My great-grandfather
was a sharecropper.

778
00:39:39.919 --> 00:39:41.876
and my dad was an auto mechanic.

779
00:39:42.005 --> 00:39:46.340
And I'm in the Oval Office talking
to the President of the United States.

780
00:39:48.303 --> 00:39:51.637
You didn't mention your grandfather.
What happened to him?

781
00:39:51.764 --> 00:39:52.845
He was a drunk.

782
00:39:53.850 --> 00:39:55.807
Progress can sometimes
skip a generation.

783
00:39:55.935 --> 00:39:58.348
Yeah.

784
00:39:58.479 --> 00:40:01.187
It's 2017.

785
00:40:01.316 --> 00:40:04.809
We should be talking about
anything and everything but this.

786
00:40:05.862 --> 00:40:07.069
But we're not. sir.

787
00:40:08.323 --> 00:40:10.083
And as long as we're having
the conversation.

788
00:40:10.116 --> 00:40:12.529
you're the person
I want to be having it with.

789
00:40:12.660 --> 00:40:14.902
You've got the boat pointed
in the right direction.

790
00:40:15.496 --> 00:40:16.657
Thank you. Mike.

791
00:40:18.499 --> 00:40:21.333
Well. here's to hoping one day.
we can all learn to row together.

792
00:40:21.878 --> 00:40:23.961
It's all we can do. sir.

793
00:40:24.088 --> 00:40:25.499
Yeah.

794
00:40:37.018 --> 00:40:40.728
All this stuff happened 30 years ago.
How did Lloyd find out about all of it?

795
00:40:40.855 --> 00:40:44.724
He's definitely looking for something
to compromise the president with.

796
00:40:44.859 --> 00:40:46.942
Well. he found a vulnerability.

797
00:40:47.070 --> 00:40:49.403
One that he's making us investigate.

798
00:40:49.530 --> 00:40:51.237
He knows law enforcement can't bury it.

799
00:40:51.366 --> 00:40:53.323
- Yeah. the problem with transparen...
- Shh.

800
00:41:31.572 --> 00:41:33.029
Eric Little.

800
